********** EEttyymmoollooggyy[[_ee_dd_ii_tt_ _ss_oo_uu_rr_cc_eeÂÂ || _ee_dd_ii_tt]] **********
The word hospitality derives from the Latin hospes,_[_3_] meaning "host", "guest",
or "stranger". Hospes is formed from hostis, which means "stranger" or "enemy"
(the latter being where terms like "hostile" derive).
********** CCuurrrreenntt uussaaggee[[_ee_dd_ii_tt_ _ss_oo_uu_rr_cc_eeÂÂ || _ee_dd_ii_tt]] **********
In the West today hospitality is rarely a matter of protection and survival,
and is more associated with _e_t_i_q_u_e_t_t_e and _e_n_t_e_r_t_a_i_n_m_e_n_t. However, it still
involves showing respect for one's guests, providing for their needs, and
treating them as equals. Cultures and subcultures vary in the extent to which
one is expected to show hospitality to strangers, as opposed to personal
friends or members of one's _i_n_-_g_r_o_u_p.
Hospitality ethics is a discipline that studies this usage of hospitality.
********** GGlloobbaall ccoonncceeppttss[[_ee_dd_ii_tt_ _ss_oo_uu_rr_cc_eeÂÂ || _ee_dd_ii_tt]] **********
******** PPaakkhhttuunnss[[_ee_dd_ii_tt_ _ss_oo_uu_rr_cc_eeÂÂ || _ee_dd_ii_tt]] ********
The _P_a_k_h_t_u_n people of South-Central Asia, predominant in the all provinces of
_A_f_g_h_a_n_i_s_t_a_n have a strong code of hospitality. They are a people characterized
by their use of an ancient set of ethics, the first principle of which is
milmastiya or "hospitality". The general area of _P_a_k_h_t_u_n_i_s_t_a_n is also nicknamed
The Land of Hospitality.
******** CCllaassssiiccaall eetthhiicc wwoorrlldd[[_ee_dd_ii_tt_ _ss_oo_uu_rr_cc_eeÂÂ || _ee_dd_ii_tt]] ********
To the ancient Greeks, hospitality was a divine right. The host was expected to
make sure the needs of his guests were seen to. The ancient Greek term _x_e_n_i_a,
or theoxenia when a god was involved, expressed this ritualized guest-
friendship relation. In Greek society a person's ability to abide the laws to
hospitality determined nobility and social standing.
******** CCeellttiicc ccuullttuurreess[[_ee_dd_ii_tt_ _ss_oo_uu_rr_cc_eeÂÂ || _ee_dd_ii_tt]] ********
Celtic societies also valued the concept of hospitality, especially in terms of
protection. A host who granted a person's request for refuge was expected not
only to provide food and shelter to his/her guest, but to make sure they did
not come to harm while under their care._[_4_]
******** IInnddiiaa[[_ee_dd_ii_tt_ _ss_oo_uu_rr_cc_eeÂÂ || _ee_dd_ii_tt]] ********
In India hospitality is based on the principle _A_t_i_t_h_i_ _D_e_v_o_ _B_h_a_v_a, meaning "the
guest is God". This principle is shown in a number of stories where a guest is
literally a god who rewards the provider of hospitality. From this stems the
Indian approach of graciousness towards guests at home, and in all social
situations.
********** SSeeee aallssoo[[_ee_dd_ii_tt_ _ss_oo_uu_rr_cc_eeÂÂ || _ee_dd_ii_tt]] **********
